[00:00.55]	[Another part of the field.,]
[00:01.67]	[Alarum. Enter KING HENRY VI alone]
[00:02.79]KING HENRY VI	This battle fares like to the morning's war,
[00:07.46]	When dying clouds contend with growing light,
[00:12.21]	What time the shepherd, blowing of his nails,
[00:16.88]	Can neither call it perfect day nor night.
[00:21.35]	Now sways it this way, like a mighty sea
[00:25.65]	Forced by the tide to combat with the wind;
[00:30.22]	Now sways it that way, like the selfsame sea
[00:34.88]	Forced to retire by fury of the wind:
[00:38.89]	Sometime the flood prevails, and then the wind;
[00:43.74]	Now one the better, then another best;
[00:47.75]	Both tugging to be victors, breast to breast,
[00:52.41]	Yet neither conqueror nor conquered:
[00:56.33]	So is the equal of this fell war.
[00:59.97]	Here on this molehill will I sit me down.
[01:04.35]	To whom God will, there be the victory!
[01:08.46]	For Margaret my queen, and Clifford too,
[01:12.65]	Have chid me from the battle; swearing both
[01:17.22]	They prosper best of all when I am thence.
[01:21.70]	Would I were dead! if God's good will were so;
[01:26.46]	For what is in this world but grief and woe?
[01:31.12]	O God! methinks it were a happy life,
[01:35.04]	To be no better than a homely swain;
[01:38.96]	To sit upon a hill, as I do now,
[01:42.41]	To carve out dials quaintly, point by point,
[01:46.98]	Thereby to see the minutes how they run,
[01:51.27]	How many make the hour full complete;
[01:55.28]	How many hours bring about the day;
[01:59.10]	How many days will finish up the year;
[02:03.21]	How many years a mortal man may live.
[02:07.22]	When this is known, then to divide the times:
[02:11.88]	So many hours must I tend my flock;
[02:15.71]	So many hours must I take my rest;
[02:19.44]	So many hours must I contemplate;
[02:23.08]	So many hours must I sport myself;
[02:26.81]	So many days my ewes have been with young;
[02:31.28]	So many weeks ere the poor fools will ean:
[02:35.76]	So many years ere I shall shear the fleece:
[02:40.33]	So minutes, hours, days, months, and years,
[02:44.53]	Pass'd over to the end they were created,
[02:48.91]	Would bring white hairs unto a quiet grave.
[02:53.48]	Ah, what a life were this! how sweet! how lovely!
[02:58.33]	Gives not the hawthorn-bush a sweeter shade
[03:03.00]	To shepherds looking on their silly sheep,
[03:07.47]	Than doth a rich embroider'd canopy
[03:11.39]	To kings that fear their subjects' treachery?
[03:16.05]	O, yes, it doth; a thousand-fold it doth.
[03:20.16]	And to conclude, the shepherd's homely curds,
[03:24.82]	His cold thin drink out of his leather bottle.
[03:29.67]	His wonted sleep under a fresh tree's shade,
[03:34.34]	All which secure and sweetly he enjoys,
[03:38.53]	Is far beyond a prince's delicates,
[03:42.36]	His viands sparkling in a golden cup,
[03:46.37]	His body couched in a curious bed,
[03:50.10]	When care, mistrust, and treason waits on him.
[03:54.76]	[Alarum. Enter a Son that has killed his father,
[03:55.32]	+ dragging in the dead body]
[03:55.88]Son	Ill blows the wind that profits nobody.
[04:00.08]	This man, whom hand to hand I slew in fight,
[04:04.65]	May be possessed with some store of crowns;
[04:09.22]	And I, that haply take them from him now,
[04:13.51]	May yet ere night yield both my life and them
[04:18.36]	To some man else, as this dead man doth me.
[04:22.84]	Who's this? O God! it is my father's face,
