[05:16.56]KING HENRY VI	O piteous spectacle! O bloody times!
[05:20.39]	Whiles lions war and battle for their dens,
[05:24.96]	Poor harmless lambs abide their enmity.
[05:29.15]	Weep, wretched man, I'll aid thee tear for tear;
[05:34.01]	And let our hearts and eyes, like civil war,
[05:38.58]	Be blind with tears, and break o'ercharged with grief.
[05:44.08]	[Enter a Father that has killed his son, bringing in the body]
[05:45.20]Father	Thou that so stoutly hast resisted me,
[05:49.30]	Give me thy gold, if thou hast any gold:
[05:53.50]	For I have bought it with an hundred blows.
[05:58.07]	But let me see: is this our foeman's face?
[06:02.45]	Ah, no, no, no, it is mine only son!
[06:06.00]	Ah, boy, if any life be left in thee,
[06:09.82]	Throw up thine eye! see, see what showers arise,
[06:14.67]	Blown with the windy tempest of my heart,
[06:19.06]	Upon thy words, that kill mine eye and heart!
[06:23.72]	O, pity, God, this miserable age!
[06:27.08]	What stratagems, how fell, how butcherly,
[06:31.27]	Erroneous, mutinous and unnatural,
[06:34.91]	This deadly quarrel daily doth beget!
[06:38.92]	O boy, thy father gave thee life too soon,
[06:43.31]	And hath bereft thee of thy life too late!
[06:47.78]KING HENRY VI	Woe above woe! grief more than common grief!
[06:52.35]	O that my death would stay these ruthful deeds!
[06:57.30]	O pity, pity, gentle heaven, pity!
[07:00.75]	The red rose and the white are on his face,
[07:05.32]	The fatal colours of our striving houses:
[07:09.70]	The one his purple blood right well resembles;
[07:14.55]	The other his pale cheeks, methinks, presenteth:
[07:19.40]	Wither one rose, and let the other flourish;
